<DOC><DOCNO> AP881003-0186 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1955EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-India-Floods     10-03 0301</FIRST><SECOND>AM-India-Floods,0314</SECOND><HEAD>Death Toll From Floods Reaches 462, Rains Kill 14 In Bombay</HEAD><DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   As flood waters receded Monday,authorities intensified relief operations in four states innorthern India, where at least 462 people have died in nearly twoweeks of flooding.   In the city of Bombay in western India, torrential rains killedat least 14 people on Monday, Indian news agencies reported.   Roads and rail communications in the city were cut off after theheaviest rainfall in a day for three decades was recorded Monday,news agencies said without giving the amount in inches.   The government said 462 people have been killed in the floods,which on Sept. 22 struck the northern states of Punjab, Haryana,Himachal Pradesh and Jammu and Kashmir.   News reports said the floods claimed as many as 800 lives.   Sidharta S. Ray, governor of Punjab, said the area's three majorrivers _ the Sutlej, Beas and Ravi _ had receded below the dangerlevel, allowing workers to step up relief efforts.   More than 250,000 people were evacuated from 1,650 villages thatare still cut off by water, Ray told reporters. More than 140,000people have left their homes and were accommodated in 242 reliefcamps, he said.   Ray said 142 people are still reported missing in Punjab, thearea worst hit by the floods.   Relief workers used boats to try to rescue trapped villagers,officials said. Helicopters dropped food supplies into floodedareas, and Indian air force transport planes delivered fuel intoareas where road and rail services were cut off.   Officials were still trying to determine the extent of cropdamage in Punjab, which produces about half the country's wheat andrice.   Floods frequently batter the subcontinent during the summermonsoon rains, which begin in late June and last through September.</TEXT></DOC>